g.aria-label: 3. Discard
Discard lowers the value of your hand with 6, while not affecting the total amount on the play ﬁeld (the limit).
To Discard, reveal a ’6’ from your hand and place it
outside of the play area. Announce the current total of the amount on the play ﬁeld. Your turn ends.
You can
not discard any other cards than 6s
4. Knock
Knock means to end the game and determine the win
ner. You can only Knock if the total amount on your
cards (both in your hand and those you have Drawn) is
equal to or lower than the total amount in the play pile.
To Knock, Announce that you Knock, reveal your
hand. Your opponent reveals his hand and you compare
your total points. If your opponent’s total exceeds the total in the play ﬁeld, you win automatically. If not, the
player with the highest total wins.
If both players have
the same total, the player who Knocked loses
Example of a Knock
Let’s say you have two 2 and one 6 in your hand. That’s
total 10. Also, you have Drawn a 5 earlier, so your total
is 15. If this is lower than or equal to the Play Field, you
may Knock if you wish.
6 point match – ﬁfth option ”Fold”
In a 6 point match you play several games in a row,
allowing for a bit more clever play. The rules are as nor
- mal, but adds a ﬁfth option – to Fold (give up).
Fold
can only be done during your turn.
Victory conditions:
If you win, you get 2 points. If your opponent Folds, you get 1 point. The ﬁrst player to 6
points wins.
Starting player switch:
The player who gained points
during the previous match becomes starting player for
the next.

Khmer English rules
Khmer is a 2-player game where the players compete
in having the highest total score on the cards in their
hands. The player with the highest total wins, but there
is a limit as to much points you may have – if you ex
ceed that by so much as 1 point, you automatically lose.
The game consist of 16 cards: Two each of 1, 2, 3, 4, and
5 and six of 6. All 6s are printed in red.
Shufﬂe the cards, and deal out 6 cards to each player.
The remaining 4 cards are placed beside the gaming
area; they are not used in the game. Decide starting
player in a suitable fashion, and the game may start.
Flow of the game
At a player’s turn, he can do one, and only one of the
following: 1. Play – play a card from hand onto the ﬁeld 2. Draw – pick up the top card from the ﬁeld
3. Discard – discard a ’6’ from hand out of the game
4. Knock – end the game, hoping you are winning.
ou can only do one of these – not Play then Kno
The game doesn’t end if you run out of cards. You
can still Draw or Knock or, if you are playing a 6 point
match, Fold.
In rare cases, if both players keep Drawing, it might
happen that you have no cards left in hand, and there are no cards in the play ﬁeld. In this case, the turn
player automatically loses. If you are playing a 6 point
match, this counts as an automatic Fold.

Play lowers the total value of your hand, and raises the value of the play ﬁeld – the allowed max point limit.

2. Draw
Draw is the opposite of Play – it raises the total value of
the cards in your possession, but lowers the value of the play ﬁeld – the allowed max point limit.
To Draw, take the
card in the play ﬁeld and place
it face up before you. Announce the current total on the play ﬁeld. Your turn ends. You can only draw the top card in the play ﬁeld. Also, you cannot Play nor Discard
the cards you have Drawn. Therefore, keep your Drawn
cards separate from your hand.
